-- в”Ђв”Ђ Salut Г  Toi в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Salut Г  Toi, now known as Libervia, is a free, decentralized, multi-frontend communication platform built on the XMPP standard, supporting messaging, blogging, calls, and file sharing.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free and open source, no cost$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2008, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$French$q$, $q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Salut Г  Toi (Libervia) Review: Features and How It Works$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Explore Salut Г  Toi, also known as Libervia, a free decentralized XMPP communication platform with multi-frontend messaging, blogging, and encrypted calls.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Salut Г  Toi, now officially rebranded as Libervia, is a free and libre, decentralized communication platform built entirely on the XMPP, or Jabber, open messaging standard. Development began around 2008 and has been led primarily by French developer Jerome Poisson, known online as Goffi, with contributions from Adrien Cossa and, more recently, funding support from NLnet and the NGI, or Next Generation Internet, initiative, which has accelerated work on features like serverless architectures and metadata reduction for privacy. The project's defining architectural idea is a single shared backend serving many different frontends, so the same account and data can be accessed through a desktop application, a command-line interface, a text user interface, a web client, and mobile-style clients, all built on a Python and Twisted async foundation with SQLAlchemy and Alembic handling data persistence. Because it is XMPP-based, Libervia is inherently federated and decentralized: users are not locked into a single server or vendor and can switch clients while keeping the same account, similar in spirit to email. Beyond one-to-one and group instant messaging, the platform supports end-to-end encryption via OMEMO and OpenPGP, audio and video calls including group conferencing, blogging and microblogging built on the XMPP PubSub extension, encrypted file sharing, decentralized issue tracking and list management, an ActivityPub gateway that lets Libervia accounts interact with Fediverse services such as Mastodon, and gateways that bridge XMPP with IRC, other legacy networks, and email. The project is released under the GNU Affero General Public License version 3 or later, a copyleft license chosen specifically to keep the surrounding ecosystem free and libre even when the software is run as a network service. As a community and association-driven open-source project rather than a commercial company, Libervia has no pricing, sales team, or corporate headquarters; it is free to self-host or run via existing XMPP infrastructure. It is best suited to privacy-conscious individuals, activists, and organizations that want a single federated identity for messaging, blogging, and calls without depending on a centralized commercial platform, and it is typically compared with other XMPP clients and Fediverse-adjacent decentralized communication tools.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '0da45043-d5e4-43e0-b1d2-e47565c3ce95';

