-- в”Ђв”Ђ Samba в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Samba is a free, open-source implementation of the SMB/CIFS networking protocol that lets Unix and Linux systems share files and printers with, and interoperate with, Windows.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free and open source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(1992, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Samba (SMB/CIFS) Review: Features, History, and Use Cases$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Discover how Samba lets Linux and Unix systems share files and printers with Windows, act as an Active Directory domain controller, and more.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Samba is a free, open-source software suite that implements the SMB and CIFS networking protocols, allowing Unix and Linux systems to share files and printers with, and interoperate with, Microsoft Windows clients and servers. The project began when Andrew Tridgell, then a PhD student at the Australian National University, wrote the first version of what would become Samba in December 1991 and January 1992, initially describing it simply as a Unix file server for DOS Pathworks after reverse-engineering the protocol used by DEC Pathworks server software with a packet sniffer. Tridgell soon realized he had implemented the NetBIOS protocol and that the software could interoperate with other PC clients; after early names like netbios for unix and smbserver ran into a trademark conflict with a commercial product named SMBserver, the project was renamed Samba, a name Tridgell found by grepping the Unix system dictionary for words containing the letters S, M, and B in that order. Tridgell marks the adoption of CVS version control in May 1996, alongside growing contributions from developers such as Jeremy Allison, as the point at which the informal project became the Samba Team, the loosely organized global community of volunteers and corporate contributors that has maintained Samba ever since. Major milestones include the 2.0.0 release in January 1999 and the 4.x series, which added full Active Directory domain controller capability alongside traditional file and print sharing. Samba is licensed under the GNU General Public License version 3 or later, and LGPLv3 or later for some libraries, having moved from GPLv2 to GPLv3 for all releases starting in the mid-2000s. As a foundational piece of open-source networking infrastructure rather than a commercial product, Samba has no company, pricing, or headquarters; it is developed by volunteers and sponsoring organizations, with recent development partly supported by funding such as the Sovereign Tech Fund. It remains the standard way for Linux, BSD, and macOS systems to join Windows networks, act as file and print servers for Windows clients, or function as a drop-in replacement for a Windows domain controller.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '592933ba-3f90-4b7b-9d93-73fb6b1fd373';

